-- Enrichment marathon batch: FreshBooks, Freshdesk, FreshRSS, Freshsales, Freshservice, Friendica, Frill, Front

-- ── FreshBooks ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$FreshBooks is a cloud accounting and invoicing platform built for self-employed professionals, freelancers, and small service businesses, combining invoicing, expense tracking, time tracking, and financial reporting in one product.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$23/month (billed monthly; discounted promotional rates and a 10% annual-billing discount are often available)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2003, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Toronto, Canada$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$Spanish$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$FreshBooks Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$FreshBooks review covering pricing, invoicing, expense and time tracking features, pros and cons, and top alternatives for freelancers and small businesses.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$FreshBooks began in January 2003 when Toronto-based designer Mike McDerment lost an invoice file and, frustrated by the lack of simple web-based invoicing tools for small service businesses, teamed up with technically-minded collaborators Levi Cooperman and Joe Sawada to build one. The trio bootstrapped the company for roughly three and a half years, reportedly working out of McDerment's parents' basement while refining the product with direct customer feedback from freelancers, consultants, and small agencies. FreshBooks incorporated and grew steadily through word of mouth in the freelance and small-agency community before institutional capital entered the picture: in 2014 the company raised a $30 million Series A round led by Oak Investment Partners, with participation from Georgian Partners and Atlas Venture, capital used to expand beyond invoicing into a broader small-business accounting suite. McDerment served as CEO from the company's earliest days until 2021, when he stepped down operationally and became executive chair, with Don Epperson taking over as CEO. FreshBooks remains headquartered in Toronto, Ontario, with additional operations supporting customers across North America, Europe, and Australia, and it operates as a privately held company.

Product-wise, FreshBooks has evolved from a pure invoicing tool into a full small-business accounting platform. Its core modules include customizable, brandable invoicing with recurring billing and multi-currency and multi-language support; expense tracking with mobile receipt scanning and bank account imports; integrated time tracking that converts billable hours directly into invoices without manual re-entry; project management and team collaboration features; client retainers and proposals; double-entry accounting reports (profit and loss, balance sheet, general ledger) on higher tiers; and mileage tracking through its mobile apps. FreshBooks Payments, its built-in payment processing layer, lets clients pay invoices online via credit card, ACH bank transfer, and other methods, and an Advanced Payments add-on unlocks a PCI-compliant virtual terminal, card-on-file storage, and automated subscription billing. The platform ships native iOS and Android apps alongside its web application, and supports integrations with tools like G Suite/Google Workspace, Gusto, Stripe, PayPal, Shopify, and various CRM and project tools through its app marketplace and Zapier connections.

On pricing, FreshBooks uses a four-tier, feature-and-client-cap model rather than per-transaction or fully usage-based pricing. As researched directly from FreshBooks' pricing page, the Lite plan is priced at $23/month (billed monthly) and supports up to 5 billable clients, with core invoicing, expense tracking, estimates, and tax reports. The Plus plan, FreshBooks' most popular tier, is $43/month and raises the billable-client cap to 50 while adding proposals, retainers, financial and accounting reports, receipt-scanning automation, and accountant access. The Premium plan is $70/month, supports unlimited billable clients, and adds customized email templates, project profitability tracking, automated client emails, and bill-capture with line-item detail. A Select plan sits above Premium with custom, sales-negotiated pricing for larger organizations, including lower payment-processing fees, dedicated phone support, included team-member seats, white-labeling (removing FreshBooks branding), and migration assistance. All paid plans include only one user account by default; additional team members cost $11 per user per month. FreshBooks frequently runs steep introductory promotions (historically up to 90% off for several months) and offers roughly a 10% discount for annual billing, plus a 30-day free trial that does not require a credit card up front. Add-ons include Advanced Payments ($20/month, included in Select) and FreshBooks Payroll (from $40/month plus a per-employee fee).

FreshBooks' target audience is squarely small: self-employed consultants, freelance creatives, small agencies, contractors, and other service-based small businesses that need professional-looking invoices and simple bookkeeping without the complexity of full enterprise accounting software. This focus differentiates it from broader competitors. QuickBooks Online is FreshBooks' most direct rival and generally offers deeper accounting depth (inventory, payroll integration, more robust reporting) aimed at slightly larger small businesses and their accountants. Xero competes on similar terms with strong accountant/bookkeeper ecosystems, especially outside North America. Wave targets the very bottom of the market with a free tier for invoicing and accounting, monetizing through payments and payroll rather than subscriptions. Zoho Books competes as part of the broader Zoho suite for businesses already using Zoho's other applications. FreshBooks differentiates primarily through its ease of use, invoicing-first design pedigree, time-tracking integration, and customer support quality, at the tradeoff of shallower native accounting depth (e.g., inventory management and payroll are more limited or handled via add-ons/partners compared to QuickBooks). Within its niche of freelancers and small service businesses, FreshBooks has built a long-standing reputation, supported by its bootstrapped origin story and long operating history dating back over two decades, as one of the more recognizable invoicing brands in the small-business software category, competing largely on simplicity and support rather than raw feature breadth.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'c9d6721c-323e-461a-9e3f-5f4dfc9baedb';

