-- ── FreshRSS ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$FreshRSS is a free, open-source, self-hosted RSS and Atom feed aggregator designed to be lightweight, multi-user, and extensible via a REST API and plugin system.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2012, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$None (community-driven open-source project; creator based in France)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$Portuguese$q$, $q$Italian$q$, $q$Dutch$q$, $q$and 30+ additional community-translated languages$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$FreshRSS Review 2026: Features, Self-Hosting and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$FreshRSS review covering self-hosted RSS aggregation, features, API compatibility, installation, pros and cons, and top open-source alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$FreshRSS is a free and open-source, self-hosted news and feed aggregator created by French developer Marien Fressinaud, who began work on the project in October 2012. Fressinaud has documented the project's origin as a personal itch: he wanted a lightweight, self-hostable alternative to hosted RSS readers after Google Reader's decline signaled the risks of depending on a single centralized, closed-source reader. He worked on FreshRSS steadily from October 2012 through the release of its first stable 1.0 version in January 2015, and the project has continued to be actively maintained by a community of contributors since. Unlike the other tools in this batch, FreshRSS is not a commercial company or startup; it has no venture funding, no headquarters, and no formal corporate structure. It is developed in the open on GitHub under the FreshRSS organization, distributed under the GNU Affero General Public License version 3 (AGPLv3), which requires that modified versions running as a network service also make their source code available to users. As of current GitHub statistics, the project has accumulated roughly 15,000 stars and 1,200 forks, reflecting a substantial and durable open-source following relative to other self-hosted RSS readers.

Technically, FreshRSS is a PHP-based web application designed to be lightweight enough to run on modest, low-cost hosting (including shared hosting and single-board computers), while still scaling to large workloads; the project documents support for managing over one million articles and tens of thousands of subscribed feeds within a single instance. It supports multi-user operation, meaning a single FreshRSS install can serve an entire household, team, or organization with separate accounts, and includes an anonymous read-only mode for publicly sharing a curated feed list. Authentication is flexible, supporting standard web-form login, HTTP authentication, and OpenID Connect for organizations wanting single sign-on. Beyond simple feed subscription, FreshRSS supports custom tags and labels for organizing articles, a command-line interface for administrative and scripting tasks, and an extension (plugin) system for community-built add-ons. A key differentiator for power users and mobile-app compatibility is FreshRSS's API layer: it exposes an API compatible with the defunct Google Reader API as well as the Fever API, which means a large ecosystem of existing third-party RSS mobile and desktop apps (built originally for Google Reader or Fever-compatible services) can connect to a self-hosted FreshRSS instance without needing FreshRSS-specific app support. FreshRSS also implements the WebSub (formerly PubSubHubbub) standard, enabling near-instant push notifications from compatible publishers such as WordPress, Blogger, Medium, and other federated software like Friendica, rather than relying purely on periodic polling. For sites that do not publish an RSS or Atom feed at all, FreshRSS includes native web-scraping support based on XPath rules, letting users construct a feed from a page's HTML structure.

Because FreshRSS is free, open-source software, there is no pricing model in the traditional sense: there are no subscription tiers, seat limits, or paid feature gates. The only cost to a user is whatever they pay for hosting infrastructure (a VPS, shared host, home server, or platforms like Docker-based self-hosting stacks), since FreshRSS itself is downloaded and run entirely under one's own control. This makes total cost of ownership highly variable but typically very low, often just a few dollars a month for a small VPS, or effectively free if run on hardware someone already owns. The project ships an official Docker image, which has become the most common deployment method among self-hosters, alongside more traditional Apache/Nginx plus PHP-FPM installation instructions in its documentation.

FreshRSS's target audience is fundamentally different from commercial feed readers like Feedly, Inoreader, or NewsBlur: it appeals to privacy-conscious individuals, systems administrators, and technically comfortable power users who prefer to own their data and infrastructure rather than trust a third-party service with their reading habits and subscription list. It is frequently recommended within the broader self-hosting and 'de-Google' communities as a lightweight alternative to running heavier RSS platforms. Its closest open-source competitors are Miniflux (a minimalist, Go-based aggregator with a stronger opinion toward simplicity and a small paid hosted option), Tiny Tiny RSS (an older, similarly self-hosted PHP-based reader with its own plugin ecosystem), and NewsBlur (which offers both a hosted commercial service and an open-source self-hosted option). Compared to these, FreshRSS is generally regarded as a strong middle ground: more feature-rich and actively maintained than many alternatives, while remaining lighter-weight than full social-reading platforms, and its broad third-party mobile app compatibility via the Google Reader/Fever API emulation is frequently cited as a practical advantage for users who want native mobile reading experiences without needing a FreshRSS-specific client.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '98aaa86f-78de-4ac7-a8a6-37ad046c4363';

