-- ── Friendica ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Friendica is a free, open-source, decentralized social networking platform in the Fediverse that federates via ActivityPub, Diaspora, and its native DFRN protocol, emphasizing privacy and rich, Facebook-style posting.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2010, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$None (volunteer-run, decentralized open-source project)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$Italian$q$, $q$and other community-translated languages$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Friendica Review 2026: Features, Federation and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Friendica review covering decentralized social networking, ActivityPub federation, privacy controls, self-hosting, pros and cons, and Fediverse alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Friendica is a free and open-source, decentralized social networking platform that is part of the broader Fediverse, the interconnected network of independently operated social platforms that communicate using shared federation protocols. The project originated in 2010 under the name Mistpark, created by developer Mike Macgirvin, and was subsequently renamed Friendika before settling on its current name, Friendica. Macgirvin built the platform in the aftermath of concerns about centralized social networks controlling user data, positioning it as a privacy-respecting, self-hostable alternative that could still interoperate with other networks rather than existing as an isolated silo. Macgirvin departed the Friendica project in 2012 to focus on a successor protocol and platform called Zot and the associated Hubzilla software, and since then Friendica has continued entirely as a community-driven, volunteer-maintained open-source project with no corporate entity or nonprofit foundation behind it; development happens in the open on the project's own Git server (git.friendi.ca, mirrored to GitHub) with contributions from developers around the world in their spare time.

Technically, Friendica's defining characteristic is its broad protocol interoperability. It was originally built around DFRN (Distributed Friends and Relations Network), its native federation protocol, and added support for the Diaspora protocol early on to interoperate with the Diaspora social network. In its December 2018 release, Friendica added support for ActivityPub, the W3C-standardized federation protocol that now underlies most of the modern Fediverse, including Mastodon, Pleroma, and other major platforms, which significantly expanded Friendica's ability to communicate bidirectionally with the wider decentralized social web. Friendica also supports OStatus, an older protocol used by legacy platforms like GNU Social, and through various connectors and add-ons it can bridge to non-federated services such as Bluesky and Tumblr, as well as traditional email via IMAP/SMTP, letting users read and reply to email threads as though they were social posts. Functionally, Friendica differentiates itself from Mastodon and other microblogging-style Fediverse platforms by supporting longer, unrestricted post lengths with rich text and BBCode formatting rather than a strict character limit, along with features reminiscent of Facebook: photo albums, an events calendar, group/forum-style pages, and fine-grained, per-post privacy controls that let users restrict individual posts to specific contacts or groups rather than relying on a single blanket audience setting. Since there is no single commercial entity, Friendica is distributed under the GNU Affero General Public License version 3 (AGPLv3), and running it requires either self-hosting your own instance (commonly called a 'pod' or 'node' in Fediverse terminology) or joining one of the many independently operated public instances run by volunteers, some of which request voluntary donations to cover hosting costs.

As is typical across the Fediverse, precise usage statistics are inherently incomplete because no single entity has visibility into the entire federated network; however, according to federation-monitoring services like the-federation.info, Friendica had roughly 99 active instances, around 2,000 to 2,100 monthly active users and roughly 5,000 users active over a six-month window, out of approximately 29,000 total registered accounts across tracked instances as of mid-2026. These figures place Friendica as a notably smaller network than Mastodon in absolute user count, though it remains one of the longer-running and more protocol-flexible projects in the Fediverse, having predated ActivityPub itself and survived multiple shifts in the decentralized social networking landscape since 2010.

Friendica's target audience consists of privacy-conscious users, Fediverse enthusiasts, and communities who specifically want Facebook-like functionality (long-form posts, photo albums, events, groups, granular per-post privacy) in a decentralized, non-corporate form, as opposed to the shorter, Twitter-like posting style that dominates Mastodon. Its closest competitors within the Fediverse and adjacent decentralized-social space include Mastodon (by far the largest and most mainstream ActivityPub platform, oriented around short-form microblogging), Hubzilla (Macgirvin's own successor project built on the Zot protocol, offering even more granular identity and permission controls), Diaspora (an early decentralized network Friendica can still federate with via the Diaspora protocol), and newer entrants like Misskey and Pleroma, which offer alternative ActivityPub-compatible server implementations with their own feature emphases. Because Friendica has no company, funding, or revenue model behind it, it does not compete on price or go-to-market resources; instead, its role in the ecosystem is defined by protocol bridging (connecting otherwise-incompatible federated and non-federated networks together) and by offering a feature set closer to a traditional social network than the minimalist, microblog-first design most other Fediverse platforms favor.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '7c0016ff-460a-49f3-a0f2-026bb26769d9';

