-- ── Front ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Front is a customer operations platform built around a collaborative shared inbox that unifies email, chat, SMS, and social messages, layered with AI tools for drafting, routing, and quality analysis.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$25/seat/month billed annually$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2013, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$250-500 employees (estimated, based on company growth reporting)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$and other supported interface languages$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Front Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Front review covering shared inbox collaboration, omnichannel messaging, AI copilot features, pricing tiers, pros and cons, and top alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Front was founded in October 2013 by Mathilde Collin and Laurent Perrin, who built the company after Collin, frustrated with how teams collaborated on shared email accounts using clunky, ad hoc workarounds, set out to build purpose-built software for team-based communication. Collin and Perrin were accepted into Y Combinator and relocated from Paris to the San Francisco Bay Area, and Front launched publicly in June 2014. Front raised its earliest capital, around $15 million, from investors including Social Capital, SoftTech VC, former Slack CEO Stewart Butterfield, and Path co-founder David Morin, an unusually strong early investor group for a company at that stage. It went on to raise a $10 million Series A from Social Capital in 2016, a $66 million Series B led by Sequoia Capital in 2018 (a round Collin reportedly closed within roughly five days), and a $65 million Series D led by Salesforce Ventures in mid-2022. In total, Front has raised approximately $204 million in venture funding across its rounds, with investors including Y Combinator, Sequoia Capital, Battery Ventures, and Salesforce Ventures, and has been reported at a valuation of roughly $1.7 billion following its later funding rounds. The company is headquartered in San Francisco, California. In a significant leadership change, Mathilde Collin transitioned out of the CEO role in 2024: Dan O'Connell joined as CEO starting mid-April 2024 and formally took over on May 1, 2024, with Collin moving into the role of executive chair, a common pattern among founder-led companies scaling past their first decade.

Front's product is built around the concept of a collaborative shared inbox: rather than routing every customer conversation into an isolated support ticket system, Front keeps messages in an email-like interface while adding team-collaboration features on top, aiming to combine the familiarity of email with the coordination benefits of a helpdesk. Messages arriving via email, SMS, live chat, social media, and WhatsApp all land in a unified inbox visible to the whole team. Conversations can be explicitly assigned to specific team members, and a 'Live Activity' feature shows in real time when a colleague is viewing or actively drafting a reply to a given message, preventing the common problem of two people replying to the same customer independently. Internal collaboration tools include @-mentions, internal comments attached to a thread, and shared drafts that let multiple people co-author a response before it's sent, giving Front more of a workspace feel than a traditional ticketing tool. On its higher-tier plans, Front expands into a genuinely omnichannel inbox spanning email, SMS, live chat, social messaging, WhatsApp, and voice, positioning it to serve as a unified customer-communication layer across an entire go-to-market or support organization rather than a single channel. Front AI is the company's suite of AI-powered capabilities layered on top of this collaborative inbox: 'Topics' automatically categorizes inbound messages for routing and reporting purposes; 'Copilot' generates real-time suggested responses to speed up agent replies; 'Autopilot' functions as an omnichannel AI agent capable of handling routine conversations with less human involvement; and 'Smart CSAT' and 'Smart QA' infer customer satisfaction and evaluate response quality automatically, reducing the need for manual quality-assurance review of every conversation. Additional platform capabilities include canned responses, message snoozing, automated routing rules, and analytics dashboards for tracking team response times and workload distribution.

On pricing, Front simplified its plan structure in 2026 from an earlier four-tier model (Starter, Growth, Scale, and Premier, ranging historically from $19 to $229 per seat per month) down to three tiers. As researched, the current Starter plan is priced at $25 per seat per month (annual billing) and is capped at 10 seats, aimed at very small teams. The Professional plan is $65 per seat per month (annual billing), capped at 50 seats, and is the tier most commonly recommended for growing support or operations teams that need the full omnichannel channel set. The Enterprise plan is $105 per seat per month (annual billing) with no seat cap, aimed at large organizations. Front advertises savings of up to 24% for choosing annual over monthly billing across its tiers. On the Starter and Professional plans, several of Front's AI capabilities are sold as separate paid add-ons rather than included: Copilot costs $20 per seat per month, Smart QA costs $20 per seat per month, and Smart CSAT costs $10 per seat per month, though a bundled QA-plus-CSAT package is available at $25 per seat per month for teams that want both.

Front's target audience spans customer support, sales, and operations teams at small-to-midsize businesses through larger enterprises that handle high volumes of external communication and need more structure and collaboration than a personal inbox provides, but want to preserve an email-native feel rather than fully abstracting communication into ticket numbers. Front's most direct competitors include traditional helpdesk platforms like Zendesk and Freshdesk, which are more ticket-centric by design; Help Scout, which occupies similar territory to Front with an email-first, less ticket-like interface, often compared head-to-head for small support teams; Gmelius and Hiver, which add shared-inbox collaboration features directly on top of existing Gmail or Google Workspace accounts rather than replacing the inbox entirely; and Intercom, which leans further into product-led, chat-first support with heavier AI bot investment. Front differentiates primarily through its emphasis on the shared-inbox metaphor and internal collaboration tooling (Live Activity, shared drafts, internal comments) rather than pure ticket-queue management, positioning itself as 'customer operations' software that spans support, sales, and account management use cases rather than a support-only helpdesk, backed by one of the more well-capitalized independent companies in the category with over $200 million in total venture funding.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'e36a0c09-82ff-48bd-9da0-38f045bb10a2';

